'''''Cabin Pressure''''' is a radio [[situation comedy|sitcom]] written and created by [[John Finnemore (writer)|John Finnemore]] and directed and produced by [[David Tyler (UK)|David Tyler]]. It follows the exploits of the eccentric crew of the single aeroplane owned by "MJN Air" as they are chartered to take all manner of items, people or animals across the world. The show stars Finnemore, [[Stephanie Cole]], [[Roger Allam]] and [[Benedict Cumberbatch]].<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b00lmcxj| title=Cabin Pressure | publisher=BBC | accessdate=10 September 2012}}</ref> The series was first broadcast on [[BBC Radio 4]] in 2008.<ref name="epguides">{{cite web| url=http://epguides.com/CabinPressure/| title=Cabin Pressure (a Titles & Air Dates Guide) | publisher=epguide.com | author=John Lavalie | accessdate=10 September 2012| date=21 June 2012}}</ref>

Critical reception to the series was positive and four series have been broadcast, along with a special 2010 Christmas Day episode.<ref name=epguides /><ref name="episodes guide">{{cite web| url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b00lmcxj/episodes/guide| title=Cabin Pressure: Episode guide | publisher=BBC | accessdate=10 September 2012}}</ref> The fourth series consisting of six episodes was broadcast in January and February 2013.<ref name="4thseries"/>  The show's finale, entitled "Zurich", was broadcast as a two-part special on 23 and 24 December 2014.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.radiotimes.com/news/2014-02-23/benedict-cumberbatch-fans-go-wild-for-actors-recording-of-the-last-ever-cabin-pressure | title=Final episode of Cabin Pressure }}</ref><ref name=FWD-final>{{cite web|last=Finnemore|first=John|title=Prepare for final descent|url=http://johnfinnemore.blogspot.co.uk/2013/11/prepare-for-final-descent.html|work=Forget What Did|accessdate=13 November 2013}}</ref> The series' opening music is [[Mikhail Glinka]]'s Overture to ''[[Ruslan and Lyudmila (opera)|Ruslan and Lyudmila]]''.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.cabinpressurefans.co.uk/the-cabin-pressure-theme-music/| title=The Cabin Pressure Theme Music | publisher=Cabin pressure Fans|date=27 November 2011| accessdate=10 September 2012}}</ref>

==Overview==

===Setting===
The story takes place at MJN Air, the world's smallest airline, consisting of just one 16-seater plane: a "Lockheed McDonnell 312", registration Golf Echo Romeo Tango India (G-ERTI), and thus nicknamed "Gerti".<ref>{{cite episode|title=Newcastle|series=Cabin Pressure|network=[[BBC]]|station=[[BBC Radio 4]]|location=[[London]]|airdate=15 July 2011|seriesno=3|number=3}}</ref> The company name derives from when owner Carolyn Knapp-Shappey (Stephanie Cole) was awarded Gerti as part of her divorce settlement with her awful Australian husband Gordon Shappey ([[Timothy West]]) and thus proudly proclaimed that Gerti was: "My Jet Now". The company is so small, with Carolyn joking that rather than an airline MJN is more of an "airdot" than an "airline", that everything is run on a tight budget and they are willing to take on any job to keep the business going. The company is based in the fictional Fitton Airport, located somewhere in the Midlands.<ref name="Fitton">{{cite episode|title=Fitton|series=Cabin Pressure|network=[[BBC]]|station=[[BBC Radio 4]]|location=[[London]]|airdate=6 August 2008|seriesno=1|number=6}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Finnemore|first=John|authorlink=John Finnemore (writer)|title=Cabin Pressure: From A To Z Booklet|publisher=[[BBC Worldwide]]|date=5 February 2015|pages=2–3|isbn=978-1-91028-199-4}}</ref>

Each episode is named after a different city (often a destination for MJN in the episode) each beginning with successive letters of the alphabet. The episodes were not broadcast in alphabetical order, but ''The Complete Cabin Pressure: From A to Z'' collection does play the episodes alphabetically.<ref name="From A To Z">{{cite web|url=http://www.comedy.co.uk/guide/radio/cabin_pressure/buy/4190/the_complete_cabin_pressure_from_a_to_z_audiobook/|title=The Complete Cabin Pressure - From A To Z (Audio)|publisher=[[British Comedy Guide]]|accessdate=6 June 2015}}</ref>

===Plot===
{{See also|List of Cabin Pressure characters}}
The story follows the day-to-day working life of MJN Air and its crew of four: Carolyn (Stephanie Cole), the owner and stewardess; First Officer Douglas Richardson (Roger Allam), an experienced pilot formerly at Air England until he was sacked for smuggling; Captain Martin Crieff (Benedict Cumberbatch), whose love of flying and planes is let down by his lack of natural ability; and Arthur Shappey (John Finnemore), Carolyn's overexcited and idiotic son who works as a steward.

Much of the plot revolves around the relationship between Douglas and Martin. While Martin is the captain, Douglas is more experienced, and most people consider Douglas to be superior to him in almost every way. When meeting both men most guests mistakenly believe Douglas to be the captain rather than Martin. Carolyn refers to Douglas as the "good pilot" and Martin as the "safe pilot".<ref>{{cite episode|title=Ipswich|series=Cabin Pressure|network=[[BBC]]|station=[[BBC Radio 4]]|location=[[London]]|airdate=31 July 2009|seriesno=2|number=3}}</ref> Also, while Douglas gets paid, Martin does not because Carolyn cannot afford it. Thus Martin also has a second job with his own business, Icarus Removals, using a van he inherited from his late father, and lives a life of poverty.<ref name="Qikiqtarjuaq">{{cite episode|title=Qikiqtarjuaq|series=Cabin Pressure|network=[[BBC]]|station=[[BBC Radio 4]]|location=[[London]]|airdate=1 July 2011|seriesno=3|number=1}}</ref>

Douglas, meanwhile, has to do his job in order to pay two different alimonies, and tries to keep secret from his third wife Helena that he is not a captain. It is later revealed that Helena is having an affair.<ref>{{cite episode|title=Limerick|series=Cabin Pressure|network=[[BBC]]|station=[[BBC Radio 4]]|location=[[London]]|airdate=21 August 2009|seriesno=2|number=6}}</ref> Douglas is also a recovering alcoholic, having been sober for a period of several years at the time the story begins, although he tries to prevent anyone else from knowing about it, fearing it will tarnish his image.<ref name="Fitton"/>

Much of the time spent on the flight-deck is spent with the crew playing various games to pass the time such as "People Who Aren't Evil But Have Evil Sounding Names", "Brians of Britain", "Books That Sound More Interesting with the Final Letter Knocked Off" (e.g. ''[[Three Men in a Boat|Three Men in a Boa]]'', ''[[Of Mice and Men|Of Mice and Me]]'') and "The Travelling Lemon", in which the crew try to hide a lemon in plain sight of the passengers without anyone complaining. This is the origin of the phrase "The lemon is in play," used by Douglas in the episodes [[Qikiqtarjuaq]] and [[Zurich]] Part 2.  <ref name="Fitton"/><ref name="Qikiqtarjuaq"/>

Though MJN squabble among themselves, in several episodes the crew unite to combat a common enemy or problem. A recurring antagonist is Gordon Shappey ([[Timothy West]]), Carolyn's ex-husband and Arthur's father, who resents Carolyn obtaining the jet in the divorce and frequently tries to reacquire it through fair means and foul. Other recurring characters include Mr Birling ([[Geoffrey Whitehead]]), who every year hires the plane to take him to see the final match in the [[Six Nations Championship|Six Nations]] Rugby Union tournament. On "Birling Day", the crew toady to Birling in the hope that he will give them all large tips. Every Birling Day Douglas attempts to steal Birling's whisky and sell it on while Carolyn and the rest of the crew try to stop him.

Another recurring character is Captain Hercules "Herc" Shipwright ([[Anthony Head]]), a former colleague of Douglas who now works at Scottish airline Air Caledonia. Herc is an occasional rival to Douglas and a love interest to Carolyn, though she is reluctant to reciprocate Herc's affections.

Princess Theresa of Liechtenstein ([[Matilda Ziegler]]) appears in the final season, first appearing when she hires MJN to take her younger brother and ruling monarch King Maxi to Fitton so he can return to school. She and Martin begin a romantic relationship.<ref>{{cite episode|title=Vaduz|series=Cabin Pressure|network=[[BBC]]|station=[[BBC Radio 4]]|location=[[London]]|airdate=23 January 2013|seriesno=4|number=3}}</ref>

In the two-part series finale Martin is given a paid job at Swiss Air, which means MJN has to close down and Gerti has to be sold. However, when Gordon tries to purchase Gerti, Arthur puts in a gigantic bid to stop his father from buying the plane. Douglas suspects that there is something valuable hidden on the plane and MJN manage to buy back Gerti. His suspicions prove correct when he discovers that Gordon had replaced the wiring of the plane with gold, not expecting that Carolyn would get the plane in their divorce. Martin concludes he is more skilled pilot than he thought, having been struggling in the past years with a poorly weighted plane, and the solution to Carolyn's financial problems has been right under her nose all along. Carolyn uses the money to secure the company's future, renaming it OJS Air ("Our Jet Still"). Martin takes up his new job securing paid employment and living close to Princess Theresa, Douglas is promoted to Captain, and Herc — who accepts a downwards career move due to his affections for Carolyn — is hired as the new First Officer. The series ends with OJS flying to Addis Ababa, bringing the alphabetical progression of cities full circle.<ref>{{cite episode|title=Zurich, Part 1|series=Cabin Pressure|network=[[BBC]]|station=[[BBC Radio 4]]|location=[[London]]|airdate=23 December 2014|seriesno=4|number=7}}</ref><ref>{{cite episode|title=Zurich, Part 2|series=Cabin Pressure|network=[[BBC]]|station=[[BBC Radio 4]]|location=[[London]]|airdate=24 December 2014|seriesno=4|number=8}}</ref>

==Reception==
Writing in ''[[The Independent]]'' newspaper, [[Nicholas Lezard]] praised the first series highly, called "the writing and performances&nbsp;... exceptional" and suggested that the show "deserves an award".<ref>{{cite news |title= Cabin Pressure, Radio 4: Scratch the surface and there's a classic British sitcom beneath |author= Nicholas Lezard |url= https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/reviews/cabin-pressure-radio-4-889553.html |newspaper= The Independent |date= 10 August 2008 |accessdate=4 March 2011 |location=London}}</ref> Gillian Reynolds of ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'' called ''Cabin Pressure'' "one of the best written, cast, acted and directed comedies on anywhere."<ref>{{cite news |title= A strike and a scandal keep Radio 4 on its toes |author= Gillian Reynolds |url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/8646083/A-strike-and-a-scandal-keep-Radio-4-on-its-toes.html |newspaper= The Telegraph |date= 18 July 2011 |accessdate=20 July 2011 |location=London}}</ref>

Partly due to the popularity of leading actor Benedict Cumberbatch, the show has a significant [[fandom]], and its final episode received a record number of requests for audience tickets for a Radio 4 comedy recording: 22,854 requests for just 200 available tickets.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.radiotimes.com/news/2013-01-09/cabin-pressure-writer-john-finnemore-on-the-joy-of-radio-crafting-comedy---and-benedict-cumberbatch |title= John Finnemore on the joy of crafting radio comedy... and Benedict Cumberbatch |author= |date= 9 January 2013 |work= Radio Times |publisher= |accessdate=21 November 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.radiotimes.com/news/2014-02-23/benedict-cumberbatch-fans-go-wild-for-actors-recording-of-the-last-ever-cabin-pressure |title= John Benedict Cumberbatch fans go wild for actor's recording of the last ever "Cabin Pressure" |author= |date= 23 February 2014 |work= Radio Times |publisher= |accessdate=21 November 2014}}</ref> It has been argued that this is an example of the [[Odagiri effect]] occurring in western media.<ref>{{cite web|last=Wolf|first=Ian|url=http://www.onthebox.com/vod-home-entertainment/anime/lgbt-tv-yuri-on-ice/|title=LGBT TV - Yuri!!! On Ice|publisher=On The Box|date=February 13, 2017|accessdate=February 13, 2017}}</ref>

===Awards===
''Cabin Pressure'' was nominated for a [[Writers' Guild of Great Britain]] award in 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.writersguild.org.uk/news-a-features/general/85-guild-awards2010-shortlists|title=Guild Awards 2010 – shortlists announced|author=|date=|work=|publisher=Writers' Guild|accessdate=4 March 2011|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110724145605/http://www.writersguild.org.uk/news-a-features/general/85-guild-awards2010-shortlists|archivedate=24 July 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref>

In 2011, John Finnemore won the Best Radio Comedy 2011, awarded by the [[Writers' Guild of Great Britain]].<ref>[http://www.writersguild.org.uk/news-a-features/general/225-writers-guild-awards-2011-winners Writers' Guild Awards 2011 – winners<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120414233051/http://www.writersguild.org.uk/news-a-features/general/225-writers-guild-awards-2011-winners |date=14 April 2012 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-15759220 | work=BBC News | title=Victoria Wood awarded top TV honour from Writer's Guild | date=17 November 2011}}</ref>

It was nominated for the Best Scripted Comedy category at the 2012 [[BBC Audio Drama Awards]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Shortlist announced for first BBC Audio Drama awards|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/ariel/16487660|date=10 January 2012|publisher=[[Ariel (newspaper)|Ariel]]}}</ref>

The series has won numerous Comedy.co.uk Awards, voted for by readers of the [[British Comedy Guide]]. The series won the award for "Best British Radio Sitcom" for 2011,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.comedy.co.uk/awards/2011/|title=The Comedy.co.uk Awards 2011|publisher=[[British Comedy Guide]]|accessdate=27 January 2015}}</ref> 2013,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.comedy.co.uk/awards/2013/|title=The Comedy.co.uk Awards 2013|publisher=[[British Comedy Guide]]|accessdate=27 January 2015}}</ref> and 2014.<ref name="Comedy 2014">{{cite web|url=http://www.comedy.co.uk/awards/2014/|title=The Comedy.co.uk Awards 2014|publisher=[[British Comedy Guide]]|accessdate=27 January 2015}}</ref> Also it was voted "Comedy of the Year" across TV and radio for 2014, making it the first radio show to be given the honour.<ref name="Comedy 2014"/>

==Episode list==
The episode titles follow an alphabetical sequence, beginning with the first episode, "Abu Dhabi", followed by "Boston" etc. In Series 2 and 3 episodes were broadcast out of the original intended order for various reasons.<ref name="newcastleblog"/> The episodes however are listed in alphabetical order in ''The Complete Cabin Pressure: From A To Z'' collection, and Finnemore has stated that the series was always meant to be heard alphabetically.<ref name="From A To Z"/>
